{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e6343a51-b5a6-424b-9c9a-915cf3dac01c","content":"The repo is empty, so I can't point you at existing examples, but here's a concise guide:\n\n## Evaluation Format\n\nA typical skill evaluation file is a **YAML list of test cases**, each with:\n\n```yaml\n- question: \"Find all products under $20 in the Electronics category\"\n  expected_tool_calls:\n    - tool: search_products\n      arguments:\n        category: \"Electronics\"\n        max_price: 20\n  expected_answer_contains:\n    - \"Electronics\"\n```\n\nEach case defines: **a natural-language prompt**, the **expected tool call(s)** (name + arguments), and **assertions on the final answer**.\n\n## What Makes a Good Evaluation Question\n\n| Principle | Example |\n|---|---|\n| **One clear intent** | \"What's the price of SKU-1234?\" |\n| **Requires the tool** | Answers shouldn't be guessable without calling the catalog |\n| **Tests argument mapping** | \"Show me red shoes under $50 sorted by rating\" — maps to multiple parameters |\n| **Tests multi-step reasoning** | \"Which category has the most items on sale?\" — may need multiple calls |\n| **Tests edge cases** | \"Find products matching ''\" or \"Search for SKU that doesn't exist\" |\n| **Has a verifiable answer** | You can assert on specific values, not just vibes |\n\n## Quick Checklist\n\n1. **Happy path** — straightforward queries that map 1:1 to a tool\n2. **Multi-parameter** — forces correct argument extraction from natural language\n3. **Multi-turn / chained** — answer from tool A feeds into tool B\n4. **Ambiguity handling** — does the LLM ask for clarification or guess?\n5. **Error cases** — missing required fields, empty results, invalid input\n\nStart with 5–10 happy-path cases, then layer in edge cases. Keep questions grounded in realistic user queries against your actual catalog schema.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9dec298f-b4be-4f66-9352-5d0608ca1f36","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository is empty, so I can't find specific documentation. But based on the custom instructions mentioning skill-validator, evaluation.yml, Models.cs, and InvestigatingResults.md, I have some context. Let me provide general guidance about MCP tool evaluation format based on my knowledge and the hints from the custom instructions.\n\nSince there's no repo content to reference, I'll give the user practical advice based on common evaluation patterns for LLM tool-use evaluations.","outputTokens":572},"id":"3acc2e3d-7457-43b5-ad8b-43eb7de4580a","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:42:59.503Z","parentId":"e58dbd40-ac7d-44bd-adf2-cd83cb7e534c"}
